    "abstract": "<jats:p> We study how to regulate a monopolistic firm using a robust-design, non-Bayesian approach. We derive a policy that minimizes the regulator\u2019s worst-case regret, where regret is the difference between the regulator\u2019s complete-information payoff and his realized payoff. When the regulator\u2019s payoff is consumers\u2019 surplus, he caps the firm\u2019s average revenue. When his payoff is the total surplus of both consumers and the firm, he offers a piece rate subsidy to the firm while capping the total subsidy. For intermediate cases, the regulator combines these three policy instruments to balance three goals: protecting consumers\u2019 surplus, mitigating underproduction, and limiting potential overproduction. (JEL D21, D42, D83, H25, L51) </jats:p>",
